A Quick Guide to Big-O Notation, Memoization, Tabulation, and Sorting Algorithms by Example

<span key="ef681cfd98f94161a87c291eea39a655"><span offset-key="ef681cfd98f94161a87c291eea39a655:0">Curating Complexity: A Guide to Big-O Notation</span></span>

#

<span key="7e9240fd05364c739f2ef1f744c1e102"><span offset-key="7e9240fd05364c739f2ef1f744c1e102:0">A Quick Guide to Big-O Notation, Memoization, Tabulation, and Sorting Algorithms by Example</span></span>

<img src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/800/0*yjlSk3T9c2_14in1.png" class="css-9pa8cd" draggable="false" />

<span key="78146849f6bb4824bdafb4036add6739">**_Curating Complexity: A Guide to Big-O Notation_**</span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

  <span key="6c63a51573064419ba1f160fe7e2fc53"><span offset-key="6c63a51573064419ba1f160fe7e2fc53:0">Why is looking at runtime not a reliable method of calculating time complexity?</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

  <span key="d4b57eeece0e4325b782150a6d7cfec3"><span offset-key="d4b57eeece0e4325b782150a6d7cfec3:0">Not all computers are made equal( some may be stronger and therefore boost our runtime speed )</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

  <span key="7a41bbef78ca45c4976e65c7c6d702fa"><span offset-key="7a41bbef78ca45c4976e65c7c6d702fa:0">How many background processes ran concurrently with our program that was being tested?</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

  <span key="c6ebc7b969514dcc935431e1908827df"><span offset-key="c6ebc7b969514dcc935431e1908827df:0">We also need to ask if our code remains performant if we increase the size of the input.</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

  <span key="46880bf70820403ab8c4d77987277887"><span offset-key="46880bf70820403ab8c4d77987277887:0">The real question we need to answering is: </span>`How does our performance scale?`<span offset-key="46880bf70820403ab8c4d77987277887:2">.</span></span>

#

<span key="dad95c942fae431196df03680c874c4c"><span offset-key="dad95c942fae431196df03680c874c4c:0">big ‘O’ notation</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

  <span key="5e66bbd27abd4f98b37a27103408893c"><span offset-key="5e66bbd27abd4f98b37a27103408893c:0">Big O Notation is a tool for describing the efficiency of algorithms with respect to the size of the input arguments.</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

  <span key="fc6fde3ed2a54ca19bcd33f5f51af042"><span offset-key="fc6fde3ed2a54ca19bcd33f5f51af042:0">Since we use mathematical functions in Big-O, there are a few big picture ideas that we’ll want to keep in mind:</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

  <span key="f84aa517ab9f4ede96e883d4d42a4cc3"><span offset-key="f84aa517ab9f4ede96e883d4d42a4cc3:0">The function should be defined by the size of the input.</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

  <span key="d6e202893e3341e493a7bb644e0dc8ec">`Smaller`<span offset-key="d6e202893e3341e493a7bb644e0dc8ec:1"> Big O is better (lower time complexity)</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

  <span key="21be6aaee3a742faacbc9ec8b38791f5"><span offset-key="21be6aaee3a742faacbc9ec8b38791f5:0">Big O is used to describe the worst case scenario.</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

  <span key="721e454830034021bc226588e47f6570"><span offset-key="721e454830034021bc226588e47f6570:0">Big O is simplified to show only its most dominant mathematical term.</span></span>

#

<span key="3318fdf59adc4c51868c7ac59ab1ade5"><span offset-key="3318fdf59adc4c51868c7ac59ab1ade5:0">Simplifying Math Terms</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

  <span key="b40cbb3fb5c54bd5a29f8ca2bfbe109d"><span offset-key="b40cbb3fb5c54bd5a29f8ca2bfbe109d:0">We can use the following rules to simplify the our Big O functions:</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

  <span key="f5850fce972249c090586b1966f9e412">`Simplify Products`<span offset-key="f5850fce972249c090586b1966f9e412:1"> : If the function is a product of many terms, we drop the terms that don't depend on n.</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

  <span key="98a2effbe6184f8abec2a86df654da1a">`Simplify Sums`<span offset-key="98a2effbe6184f8abec2a86df654da1a:1"> : If the function is a sum of many terms, we drop the non-dominant terms.</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

  <span key="8176cf26ac784ea1a9823669b3231aa8">`n`<span offset-key="8176cf26ac784ea1a9823669b3231aa8:1"> : size of the input</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

  <span key="5df5f64bbba64391bd90e780846c6749">`T(f)`<span offset-key="5df5f64bbba64391bd90e780846c6749:1"> : unsimplified math function</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

  <span key="0c1262acedcb4434908073983c40b000">`O(f)`<span offset-key="0c1262acedcb4434908073983c40b000:1"> : simplified math function.</span></span>

<span key="f3490d349d63475c8e16290a63f73174">`Putting it all together`</span><span slate-void="true" key="70778c68add84d19aea4d5124a195935"></span>

<img src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/800/1*TT8uuv1x3nmGUw5rvtoZ8A.png" class="css-9pa8cd" draggable="false" />

<span key="fa35d265cae34141a17468f6d90894be"><span offset-key="fa35d265cae34141a17468f6d90894be:0"><span slate-zero-width="z">​</span></span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

  <span key="55bbe959742648179bf0d74ee44a27f5"><span offset-key="55bbe959742648179bf0d74ee44a27f5:0">First we apply the product rule to drop all constants.</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

  <span key="e97eb806995a4a6fa159a8421477b371"><span offset-key="e97eb806995a4a6fa159a8421477b371:0">Then we apply the sum rule to select the single most dominant term.</span></span>

#

<span key="cf0ad6b6d3d946308885496ff6bb69a6"><span offset-key="cf0ad6b6d3d946308885496ff6bb69a6:0">Complexity Classes</span></span>

<span key="a56d9bd4ae0c47be99a6605a0158e1ab"><span offset-key="a56d9bd4ae0c47be99a6605a0158e1ab:0">Common Complexity Classes</span></span>

##

<span key="d77b372e42b44b989794c043a13ecae6"><span offset-key="d77b372e42b44b989794c043a13ecae6:0">There are 7 major classes in Time Complexity</span></span>

<img src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/800/1*6zKhmJoHkvDbrd8jfUDf3A.png" class="css-9pa8cd" draggable="false" />

##

<span key="b33eb79103c74a62950a768b047e899b">`O(1) Constant`</span>

> <span key="73af336ea7b24984aca09a17208e2097">**The algorithm takes roughly the same number of steps for any input size.**</span>

##

<span key="7e336914fc0b48c8ad68dce471577050">`O(log(n)) Logarithmic`</span>

> <span key="33148a79c84f4914b5efcf4b1910b4d6">**In most cases our hidden base of Logarithmic time is 2, log complexity algorithm’s will typically display ‘halving’ the size of the input (like binary search!)**</span>

##

<span key="f068cf9831d3432b81a5df62c6bd41e0">`O(n) Linear`</span>

> <span key="05f16a6979204c4bb81daabba38955a4">**Linear algorithm’s will access each item of the input “once”.**</span>

#

<span key="6192e34f310044f38ca18f0a890ab7dc">`O(nlog(n)) Log Linear Time`</span>

> <span key="7b751dc1812e4dd9bc1441e813a47456">**Combination of linear and logarithmic behavior, we will see features from both classes.**</span>

> <span key="0775009bc619448da692ed194fe89eea"><span offset-key="0775009bc619448da692ed194fe89eea:0">Algorithm’s that are log-linear will use </span>**both recursion AND iteration.**</span>

#

<span key="3ee02b85d07c46f990039a3be840f9a0">`O(nc) Polynomial`</span>

> <span key="c8acbd7d4531411b842ab2173dc2a343">**C is a fixed constant.**</span>

#

<span key="159c9310bc71461cb6e9c47c1b29a59e">`O(c^n) Exponential`</span>

> <span key="74f5f6bf64de49398c1ed4a0446d9a92">**C is now the number of recursive calls made in each stack frame.**</span>

> <span key="ba07c57cc988408b9975b18fd81bd34e">**Algorithm’s with exponential time are VERY SLOW.**</span>

#

<span key="156abde3704b42718838bdff8d5a8b65"><span offset-key="156abde3704b42718838bdff8d5a8b65:0">Tabulation</span></span>

##

<span key="343fc9157cd94013b91038c1ca854957"><span offset-key="343fc9157cd94013b91038c1ca854957:0">Tabulation Strategy</span></span>

> <span key="a0802a245cbe4204ac1219e45ff76a59"><span offset-key="a0802a245cbe4204ac1219e45ff76a59:0">Use When:</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

  <span key="6612cf2dcbf64a188d77e4ed5aee4a3c">**The function is iterative and not recursive.**</span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

  <span key="cff72db87f8748c7b3843d78a7f973a9">_The accompanying DS is usually an array._</span>

##

<span key="e340da7e8f3e455ba85823a459dd725f"><span offset-key="e340da7e8f3e455ba85823a459dd725f:0">Steps for tabulation</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

  <span key="45d30962048c43f6890aa585fd1248b5">_Create a table array based off the size of the input._</span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

  <span key="44041decffa6466e842a68b1c071e60e">_Initialize some values in the table to ‘answer’ the trivially small subproblem._</span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

  <span key="f4d4b2b7cf4e4daa8b47769a3d3ab161">_Iterate through the array and fill in the remaining entries._</span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

  <span key="5ee2a6710e0e4037ad3a60cc1e8a1d7a">_Your final answer is usually the last entry in the table._</span>

<span key="6991e9e15831434c8b9d9ca3f794b773"><span offset-key="6991e9e15831434c8b9d9ca3f794b773:0">Sorting Algorithms</span></span>

#

<span key="2dcf446686ef40cb941ad2d86c76c199"><span offset-key="2dcf446686ef40cb941ad2d86c76c199:0">Bubble Sort</span></span>

<span key="7953a45905814756b6d40a57aa96a88c">`Time Complexity`<span offset-key="7953a45905814756b6d40a57aa96a88c:1">: Quadratic O(n^2)</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm r-1vzi8xi" />

  <span key="34374e9cd9834e95a9913ae870403f85"><span offset-key="34374e9cd9834e95a9913ae870403f85:0">The inner for-loop contributes to O(n), however in a worst case scenario the while loop will need to run n times before bringing all n elements to their final resting spot.</span></span>

<span key="d8fd0d671c0242c48ec704f227722d8b">`Space Complexity`<span offset-key="d8fd0d671c0242c48ec704f227722d8b:1">: O(1)</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm r-1vzi8xi" />

  <span key="2808a1866de24eb086199fa90b506b88"><span offset-key="2808a1866de24eb086199fa90b506b88:0">Bubble Sort will always use the same amount of memory regardless of n.</span></span>

<img src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/800/0*Ck9aeGY-d5tbz7dT" class="css-9pa8cd" draggable="false" />

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm r-1vzi8xi" />

  <span key="98e9ad9d2672459b963b4f321eeaddc3"><span offset-key="98e9ad9d2672459b963b4f321eeaddc3:0">The first major sorting algorithm one learns in introductory programming courses.</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm r-1vzi8xi" />

  <span key="aad72759c21942fc88273af66ca7b9d5"><span offset-key="aad72759c21942fc88273af66ca7b9d5:0">Gives an intro on how to convert unsorted data into sorted data.</span></span>

> <span key="bbd9ec5b9ae14c7aa1f6cafe2ea648b7"><span offset-key="bbd9ec5b9ae14c7aa1f6cafe2ea648b7:0">It’s almost never used in production code because:</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm r-1vzi8xi" />

  <span key="0c097f1515e34f4a830db7f348de0fac">_It’s not efficient_</span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm r-1vzi8xi" />

  <span key="a5082eecec644022a84f401548b0d09d">_It’s not commonly used_</span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm r-1vzi8xi" />

  <span key="b22eab5ea5e540e59b582726c62a1ea1">_There is stigma attached to it_</span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm r-1vzi8xi" />

  <span key="ba30a9c094ca407f9e6015f259c501b4">`Bubbling Up` _: Term that infers that an item is in motion, moving in some direction, and has some final resting destination._</span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm r-1vzi8xi" />

  <span key="851bffa788c94c748ff8f2f9486cb994">_Bubble sort, sorts an array of integers by bubbling the largest integer to the top._</span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm r-1vzi8xi" />

  <span key="02e8de5720e04ee49cff996a5dab2fe9">_Worst Case & Best Case are always the same because it makes nested loops._</span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm r-1vzi8xi" />

  <span key="b125bd52933c44baabf9c642f9a51419">_Double for loops are polynomial time complexity or more specifically in this case Quadratic (Big O) of: O(n²)_</span>

#

<span key="cfd2da7f46064d2f851ed33e4cd1a222"><span offset-key="cfd2da7f46064d2f851ed33e4cd1a222:0">Selection Sort</span></span>

<span key="dab72b6b78684052811826e8686ed9fa">`Time Complexity`<span offset-key="dab72b6b78684052811826e8686ed9fa:1">: Quadratic O(n^2)</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm r-1vzi8xi" />

  <span key="f142b1a430c14b2d8aaa451089e7fa44"><span offset-key="f142b1a430c14b2d8aaa451089e7fa44:0">Our outer loop will contribute O(n) while the inner loop will contribute O(n / 2) on average. Because our loops are nested we will get O(n²);</span></span>

<span key="ddb243bbdfcb4adea20e2f438c3112a4">`Space Complexity`<span offset-key="ddb243bbdfcb4adea20e2f438c3112a4:1">: O(1)</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm r-1vzi8xi" />

  <span key="8e01c942130b40fdb282604b4cfa815b"><span offset-key="8e01c942130b40fdb282604b4cfa815b:0">Selection Sort will always use the same amount of memory regardless of n.</span></span>

<img src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/800/0*AByxtBjFrPVVYmyu" class="css-9pa8cd" draggable="false" />

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm r-1vzi8xi" />

  <span key="12397b0e3fc94c489e385754adb4fa08"><span offset-key="12397b0e3fc94c489e385754adb4fa08:0">Selection sort organizes the smallest elements to the start of the array.</span></span>

<img src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/800/0*GeYNxlRcbt2cf0rY" class="css-9pa8cd" draggable="false" />

> <span key="f89ece0cc0c846a7a742d191c3f0dfe6"><span offset-key="f89ece0cc0c846a7a742d191c3f0dfe6:0">Summary of how Selection Sort should work:</span></span>

1.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height: 24px">1.</span>
    <span key="e18a5eea43914c3585cf19707bbb5a0a">_Set MIN to location 0_</span>

2.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height: 24px">2.</span>
    <span key="dfa3e378517a466a807c909389014ee4">_Search the minimum element in the list._</span>

3.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height: 24px">3.</span>
    <span key="f8b5a9b7e7f344a5b872b20f26d645d2">_Swap with value at location Min_</span>

4.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height: 24px">4.</span>
    <span key="7cad55f43be84256be2193747a499776">_Increment Min to point to next element._</span>

5.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height: 24px">5.</span>
    <span key="68ff4debfeed46268fd9f4cde2696e47">_Repeat until list is sorted._</span>

#

<span key="4e33c6f5aaf24ec0899bd6cc8765222f"><span offset-key="4e33c6f5aaf24ec0899bd6cc8765222f:0">Insertion Sort</span></span>

<span key="2cddb7b1fe224f3f8ee6e57c729c9b8a">`Time Complexity`<span offset-key="2cddb7b1fe224f3f8ee6e57c729c9b8a:1">: Quadratic O(n^2)</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm r-1vzi8xi" />

  <span key="52caf2776347479cb1ebd824eb454220"><span offset-key="52caf2776347479cb1ebd824eb454220:0">Our outer loop will contribute O(n) while the inner loop will contribute O(n / 2) on average. Because our loops are nested we will get O(n²);</span></span>

<span key="5d10cd6f96db4f41ae13c87fc4012f6d">`Space Complexity`<span offset-key="5d10cd6f96db4f41ae13c87fc4012f6d:1">: O(n)</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm r-1vzi8xi" />

  <span key="57258624aafb4b0697dba77e180cbee6"><span offset-key="57258624aafb4b0697dba77e180cbee6:0">Because we are creating a subArray for each element in the original input, our Space Comlexity becomes linear.</span></span>

<img src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/800/0*gbNU6wrszGPrfAZG" class="css-9pa8cd" draggable="false" />

<span key="b78e13b8637b488585fb08d391b31c7a"><span offset-key="b78e13b8637b488585fb08d391b31c7a:0">Merge Sort</span></span>

<span key="a02f917e8cb147dfa0c75298a4746b29">`Time Complexity`<span offset-key="a02f917e8cb147dfa0c75298a4746b29:1">: Log Linear O(nlog(n))</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm r-1vzi8xi" />

  <span key="1e6b8b2aa9a0487581b5a5511fb0c3d8"><span offset-key="1e6b8b2aa9a0487581b5a5511fb0c3d8:0">Since our array gets split in half every single time we contribute O(log(n)). The while loop contained in our helper merge function contributes O(n) therefore our time complexity is O(nlog(n)); </span>`Space Complexity`<span offset-key="1e6b8b2aa9a0487581b5a5511fb0c3d8:2">: O(n)</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm r-1vzi8xi" />

  <span key="b2cf0fb2848140699dfcd3f51d47c4f2"><span offset-key="b2cf0fb2848140699dfcd3f51d47c4f2:0">We are linear O(n) time because we are creating subArrays.</span></span>

<span key="ca540104f5f942bc881957e236f060fc"><span offset-key="ca540104f5f942bc881957e236f060fc:0">Example of Merge Sort</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm r-1vzi8xi" />

  <span key="f2759b0642204f57968e686a293a3b2d">**Merge sort is O(nlog(n)) time.**</span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm r-1vzi8xi" />

  <span key="86da24c135ec45e1b5523205cb8d4407">_We need a function for merging and a function for sorting._</span>

> <span key="73df1b0c6aca4f16939d9d94fe85d7dc"><span offset-key="73df1b0c6aca4f16939d9d94fe85d7dc:0">Steps:</span></span>

1.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height: 24px">1.</span>
    <span key="e959b3dec31f428aac8c6dbc4f36916d">_If there is only one element in the list, it is already sorted; return the array._</span>

2.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height: 24px">2.</span>
    <span key="bf2d051174ac45009d59ef201c586851">_Otherwise, divide the list recursively into two halves until it can no longer be divided._</span>

3.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height: 24px">3.</span>
    <span key="16ba8a8f8d004d06a3f70e9d3dc893cd">_Merge the smallest lists into new list in a sorted order._</span>

<span key="be35a1a91ecb4ca68903c01f56d92a9d"><span offset-key="be35a1a91ecb4ca68903c01f56d92a9d:0">Quick Sort</span></span>

<span key="e66d8b478892445bab77502eb0404318">`Time Complexity`<span offset-key="e66d8b478892445bab77502eb0404318:1">: Quadratic O(n^2)</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm r-1vzi8xi" />

  <span key="a143ae9409f749228ec1001fa100ea09"><span offset-key="a143ae9409f749228ec1001fa100ea09:0">Even though the average time complexity O(nLog(n)), the worst case scenario is always quadratic.</span></span>

<span key="df9eaa62167a4cfdacf892f62e9c1ad3">`Space Complexity`<span offset-key="df9eaa62167a4cfdacf892f62e9c1ad3:1">: O(n)</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm r-1vzi8xi" />

  <span key="5477db8a9fda488db31ed654ab21c707"><span offset-key="5477db8a9fda488db31ed654ab21c707:0">Our space complexity is linear O(n) because of the partition arrays we create.</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm r-1vzi8xi" />

  <span key="372d95dacfce4900b74553275d8428ac"><span offset-key="372d95dacfce4900b74553275d8428ac:0">QS is another Divide and Conquer strategy.</span></span>

  <span key="8d9ddb3435214c568e5666c5fcd9695c"><span offset-key="8d9ddb3435214c568e5666c5fcd9695c:0">Some key ideas to keep in mind:</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm r-1vzi8xi" />

  <span key="e53bcc6cbb264253aee91d003fe51df3"><span offset-key="e53bcc6cbb264253aee91d003fe51df3:0">It is easy to sort elements of an array relative to a particular target value.</span></span>

  <span key="da4d03a675c048be8847c3d29bcbba91"><span offset-key="da4d03a675c048be8847c3d29bcbba91:0">An array of 0 or 1 elements is already trivially sorted.</span></span>

<span key="aa412551d8c742cfa5a9289f2e6208f2">`Space Complexity`<span offset-key="aa412551d8c742cfa5a9289f2e6208f2:1">: O(1)</span></span><span slate-void="true" key="11b21b6fa6fc4b0d9fbbd828df6ad7ea"></span>

#

<span key="cf73aea87f864208bb3a3a8eda11bf3a"><span offset-key="cf73aea87f864208bb3a3a8eda11bf3a:0">Insertion Sort</span></span>

- <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm r-1vzi8xi" />

  <span key="c6928a3a30a44802b8024f07926a4207">**Works by building a larger and larger sorted region at the left-most end of the array.**</span>

> <span key="4d0453de0ee04eef810f774c0e0d9728"><span offset-key="4d0453de0ee04eef810f774c0e0d9728:0">Steps:</span></span>

1.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height: 24px">1.</span>
    <span key="cf8e43f634c14e638a0c3e6652f0984c">_If it is the first element, and it is already sorted; return 1._</span>

2.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height: 24px">2.</span>
    <span key="d79f72e42a3c4b7e87e11a160ceef118">_Pick next element._</span>

3.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height: 24px">3.</span>
    <span key="92a9d5c49da74951bd996649a3eec60e">_Compare with all elements in the sorted sub list_</span>

4.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height: 24px">4.</span>
    <span key="d7b282a45d8e40de804889671012a6f2">_Shift all the elements in the sorted sub list that is greater than the value to be sorted._</span>

5.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height: 24px">5.</span>
    <span key="b5cc5f3ddee5495885050333b5efb315">_Insert the value_</span>

6.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height: 24px">6.</span>
    <span key="a3752d640f8c46d4ad995bcb02aefb49">_Repeat until list is sorted._</span>
